##Special Report: In the face of the escalation of the epidemic, we ask 10 key questions

Hi, Monica and Monica

Function description, here is the "First Finance" magazine (predecessor "first finance weekly") readers club, we discover wonderful business value for you, also invited you to explore the bright business world.

With the increase of the news of the epidemic, all kinds of "rumors" about its source, how to spread and control have followed. To that end, we asked professionals in the relevant fields to try to answer 10 questions that are of the greatest concern to the public.

Reporter | Xu Bingqing Xiao Wenjie Ni Zhang Yunting Xiang Weixiao, Mao Yimei

Intern reporter | Wen Simin

Data collation | intern reporter, Yuan Ying

Charting | Cheng Xing, Wang Fanghong

The COVID-19, which originated in Wuhan, is still spreading. As of 2400 hours on January 23rd, 830 cases of COVID-19 had been confirmed nationwide. Perhaps a small consolation is that, starting on January 20th, the epidemic is finally getting more attention across China.

At the Shanghai Hongqiao Railway Station on Jan. 22, many Spring Festival travelers chose to wear masks. | by Wang Yiyue

But as news of the outbreak grew, so did "rumors" about its source and how it could be spread and controlled. To this end, YiMagazine interviewed researchers working on the virus genome, epidemiologists, public health researchers, Health Commission insiders and Urban Science Researcher Mao Mingrui, among others, try to answer the ten questions you care about most, but may still be full of questions.

01
How should China's health care system function in the face of such an epidemic?

The system for dealing with infectious diseases is made up of many departments. The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) at all levels may be at the heart of it. It is a government-funded institutions, health committees at all levels. Dealing with infectious diseases is an important part of its job. It has the technical expertise, the laboratories to detect pathogens, and the expertise to conduct epidemiological investigations. If there is an outbreak of an infectious disease, the approach goes something like this:
1) Doctors Find Official Infectious;
2) the hospital reports to the local CDC via the network system;
3) the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention will send epidemiologic investigators for exposure history and other information;
4) investigators will also collect samples from patients for analysis by a professional laboratory;
5) the results of the investigation and testing will be reported to the Health Commission;
6) a common infectious disease may stop there, but if it gets worse, it could trigger a response. If you want to move hospital beds, doctors, increased protection, isolation, transfer patients, these things do not belong to the CDC. The health commission issues circulars through the Medical Administration branch, which is specialized in the management of Hospitals;
7) when an unusual situation warrants attention, the health commission quickly mobilizes national experts and sets up a team of experts who will make recommendations directly to the government on how to handle it, as it did in this case.
Local governments have taken into account new and undiscovered infectious diseases in their preparedness plans for public health incidents, but in such cases, whether they can be reported, investigated and disposed of in a timely manner, much depends on the experience and execution of the health care system and local governments. At this point, speed is the key.

02
If I am in the hospital fever clinic, how will the hospital reduce my probability of being infected?

First of all, the hospital will strengthen the management of cleaning and disinfection work, such as strengthening the ventilation of the treatment environment. Conditional medical institutions will implement air disinfection, can also be equipped with circulating air disinfection equipment. The environment for diagnosis and treatment, medical equipment, patients with objects will also do cleaning and disinfection.

Secondly, hospitals should try to reduce the congestion of patients in order to reduce the risk of hospital infection. If a patient is suspected or diagnosed with COVID-19, quarantine or control of transmission measures shall be taken in accordance with the law, and medical observation shall be made of the patient's attendants and other close contacts, as required, and other necessary precautions. Do not have the ability to cure, timely referral of patients to have the ability to cure the medical institutions.

In the near future, medical institutions will also help patients and their escorts actively understand the COVID-19 education, guidance on proper hand washing, cough etiquette and home isolation.

03
We have experienced SARS, what experience is helpful to the management of this epidemic?

The current system of infectious disease prevention and control in China was basically established after the SARS epidemic in 2003.

The Communicable Disease Prevention Act was enacted in 2004. Among them, for the first time, several important principles were established, such as the obligation for all hospital cases of infectious diseases to be reported to the health department, which had not previously been the obligation of military hospitals; and, for example, in this law, for the first time, the method of "Class B infectious disease, take the prevention and control measures of Class A infectious disease" was put forward. This time, the COVID-19 pneumonia followed the same criteria.

Moreover, after 2003, the Chinese government's health expenditure increased rapidly. In 2003 it was 111.6 billion yuan, a 13 fold increase in 2018.

* Total health expenditure = government health expenditure + social health expenditure + personal health expenditure
The definitions and calculations of total health expenditure and government health expenditure are explained in the National Bureau of Statistics of the People's Republic of China

Today, every province and city has a special hospital for infectious disease patients. Usually, they will receive a variety of patients, and when other hospitals have a specific infectious disease, general referral here, as well as other designated hospitals, such as tuberculosis, AIDS and so on. When there is an outbreak like SARS, it can be the first to set up isolation wards.

The Public Health Center in Shanghai, for example, was set up after the SARS epidemic. Pipes were buried under the hospital lawns. In case of emergency, the makeshift wards could be set up directly for centralized isolation and treatment.

04
So far, are we facing a more serious situation than we did during SARS?

The epidemic spread of infectious diseases is a model full of variables. The nature of the disease itself, the density of people in the area, the flow of people, the timing of preventive measures, and the weather all have an impact. So there's no exact analogy, but there are several points in time.

The prevention and treatment of all infectious diseases can be solved by "three measures" : 1) controlling the source of infection, 2) cutting off the route of transmission, and 3) protecting the susceptible population.

On the first thing, we're moving faster this time than we did when we had SARS.

On December 30, the medical administration and Medical Administration Department of Wuhan Health Commission issued an emergency notice on the treatment of pneumonia of unknown cause, saying that since December, pneumonia of unknown cause has started to appear in Wuhan.

On January 7, CDC experts isolated the COVID-19; on January 10, professor Zhang Yongzhen of the Fudan University and his team published the full genome sequence of the virus on the academic website of global viral research.

In other words, it took less than a month from the onset of the disease to the identification of the pathogen.

SARS, on the other hand, took five months for the coronavirus to be detected by foreign scientists and confirmed by WHO as the pathogen.

Next, it is directed at the characteristics of pathogens and diseases, rapid prevention and control. This is not just a matter of the health care system, because information disclosure, disease control, mobilization and other work, need to be completed by the government.

But since January 11, the number of confirmed cases announced by the Wuhan Municipal Health and Health Commission has risen from 41 to 45 until January 16. On January 20th the Official infectious included the disease in its list of diseases.

REPORTER: First Finance and Economics, Wu Mianqiang

05
"Wuhan Pneumonia" before spreading to the whole country, why did not break out first in Hubei Province?

On the subject, cEO  , founder of urban quadrant and Secretary General of Cloud Platform Innovation Center of Beijing Urban Planning & Design Institute, and his team conducted a comprehensive study of tencent migration data and other data from 2018 to 2019, some interesting perspectives are given as to why

1) cities in Hubei Province, as well as cities in and around Hubei Province such as Yueyang, Xinyang and Jiujiang, should strengthen the screening of long-distance bus passengers from the "Wuhan Metropolitan Area" (Note: With Wuhan as the center, covering the urban cluster of eight large and medium-sized cities around Huangshi, Ezhou, Huanggang, Xiaogan, Xianning, Xiantao, Xianning and Tianmen) .

This is because the inner cities of the metropolitan area have daily high frequency contact with the inner cities, even commuting. However, only Huanggang has been reported in the figures so far, so there is a possibility that the situation in Hubei Province is underestimated or not properly accounted for.

2) cities such as Beijing, Shanghai, Chengdu, Guangzhou, Changsha, Xiangyang, Jingzhou and Yichang should strengthen the screening of railway passengers from Wuhan; cities such as Beijing, Kunming, Shenyang and Chengdu should also strengthen the screening of flights from Wuhan.

Among these cities, Changsha and Kunming are the new first-tier cities with high degree of contact with Wuhan, but the number of epidemic people is still relatively small. These two cities are the central cities of their respective metropolitan areas, but also an important node of the urban agglomerations, so the two cities if the outbreak of disease, there is a certain ability to spread.

3) the spread of "Wuhan Pneumonia" to Beijing, Shanghai, Guangzhou, Shenzhen, several first-tier cities, medical conditions, information transparency, as well as anti-sars experience, the people's awareness of self-protection is high, so the situation is relatively optimistic.

In addition to presenting the results of the current analysis, Mao Mingrui also stressed that the current epidemic areas must disclose detailed public data, so as to effectively increase the awareness of self-protection of residents in the epidemic areas. The current practice of opening up data according to the province is not conducive to civil protection, not conducive to appropriate responses from all sectors, and not conducive to scholars carrying out valuable research.

06
There is no vaccine or specific drug for COVID-19, so how long will it take for the vaccine to be developed, marketed, and then marketed to consumers?

During the SARS outbreak, academician Zhong Nanshan proposed the treatment of "hormone shock therapy" , because large doses of glucocorticoid shock can effectively control this immune pathological response, glucocorticoid was then heavily used in the emergency treatment of SARS. But it has also led to osteonecrosis of the femoral head in many patients, as well as pulmonary dysfunction and other drug side effects.

After sequencing the genome of the COVID-19, the U.S. now includes teams at the NIH and the Baylor College of Medicine, as well as in Texas and New York, and at the University of Saskatchewan in Canada, and a team of Chinese scientists are already working on a vaccine.

"coronaviruses are a relatively simple vaccine target, " says Peter Hotz, a vaccine scientist at the Baylor College of Medicine, so they are less difficult to develop than vaccines against other viruses, such as HIV or influenza.

After the vaccine is developed, it is expected to take several months to complete the first phase of clinical trials and wait more than a year for its official launch.

07
Where is the "new" COVID-19 of 2020 compared with the SARS virus?

There are six previously known human coronaviruses: Four of them are more common in humans and less pathogenic; the other two, SARS coronavirus and Mers coronavirus, cause severe respiratory disease.

This COVID-19 is different from all known human coronaviruses.

On January 10,2020, Professor Zhang Yongzhen's team at Fudan University published the genome sequence of Covid-19 for the first time on the virological.org  . Based on the genome sequence, hao Pei, a researcher at the Shanghai Pasteur Institute of the Chinese Academy of Sciences, and his team published their findings on Jan. 21 in the Journal COVID-19. In the paper, Hao and his team reveal the origin of the COVID-19 virus and its genetic relationship to SARS coronavirus and MERS coronavirus.

The COVID-19 virus is similar to the SARS virus in that it acts as an immunopathologic response -- as if when the virus enters the body, it invades living cells, inducing them to attack their own cells, this leads to a severe inflammatory reaction.

08
Where does COVID-19 come from, and what is its infectiousness and variability?

After the SARS outbreak in 2003, researchers discovered that the SARS coronavirus was transmitted by "bat-civet-man" , and the international community later discovered that bats were the coronavirus's stronghold. Hao's team compared the entire genome of COVID-19, SARS coronavirus and Mers coronavirus to find that the viruses share a common ancestor. Therefore, the natural host of Wuhan Coronavirus may also be bats.

A paper published Jan. 22 in the Journal of Medicalvirology by Peking University, the Guangxi University of Chinese Medicine, the Ningbo University and others suggests, snakes are the most likely wildlife reservoir to cause the current Covid-192019-ncov outbreak. In other words, the COVID-19 may have traveled the same route as the bat-snake-man.

According to Hao's team, COVID-19 shares the same pathogenesis as the SARS virus, which infects humans through the interaction of the S-protein with human ACE2 in COVID-19 Pseudostratified columnar epithelium, this means that the virus provides a basis for human-to-human transmission.

In an interview with the CCTV-13 News 1 + 1, Academician Zhong Nanshan confirmed to the public that the COVID-19 will "pass from one person to another. " .

In an interview with the Beijing News on Jan. 21, WHO officials said that the latest reported infection "has no clear evidence of sustained human-to-human COVID-19. ". According to Zhu Huachen, an associate professor at the public health of the University of Hong Kong who has long studied viral emerging infectious diseases, "the transmission of the virus is cut off after one or two generations" , making it difficult to achieve efficient transmission or even super-transmission.

When the latest case data were released on Jan. 22, Li Bin, deputy director of the COVID-19, said there was still a possibility of mutation.

On the morning of January 22 local time, the World Health Organization convened an emergency committee meeting in Geneva. After two days of discussion, the World Health Organization Organization announced at a press conference held in the evening of January 23 local time and in the early hours of January 24 China Standard Time, the COVID-19 outbreak will not be defined as "a public health emergency of international concern" for the time being.

According to the definition of the IHR, an "international public health emergency" means "a public health risk to other countries through the international spread of a disease" , and may require a coordinated "international response" to "extraordinary" events. Since the rules were introduced in the Mid-2000s, only five announcements have been made about H1N1, poliomyelitis, Ebola and Zika.

09
Is it credible to predict that the number of people infected with COVID-19 pneumonia in Wuhan would be in the thousands?

At present, non-traditional public health data such as traffic data, mobile communication data and social media data can be used to help estimate and even predict epidemic risk. Both the Imperial College London's MRC Global Infectious Disease Analysis Centre and the public health used Wuhan traffic data as a key basis for modelling the COVID-19 outbreak.

In the MRC's research methods, it is mainly to use the confirmed cases reported from abroad to push back the situation in Wuhan, there are four key parameters in the model: The number of confirmed cases abroad, the number of passengers departing from Wuhan Airport every day, the number of passengers per day at Wuhan Airport, and the average incubation period of the virus. The data for these four parameters is inherently elastic (for example, the Virus latency is usually estimated at 10 days, but it could also be 8 days) , so the estimated number of infected people is a large range.

Using the data reported by the government on January 18, the MRC has given the upper and lower limits of the maximum number of people infected in Wuhan on January 18, ranging from 1,000 to 9,700 respectively, and the maximum possible value of 4,000 under standard parameters. (see MRC report in News / Wuhan Coronavirus)

At a press conference of the State Council Office on January 22, responding to the findings, Takatomi, an academician at the Chinese Academy of Sciences and Director of the Chinese Center for Disease Control and Prevention, said: "everyone knows that to recognize any new thing, especially a virus like this, must be 'fact is fact, knowledge theory is theory' . And I think that as you know more about this virus, you will be able to test this model. "What we know now is not the model that the scientist has calculated. "

The mathematical model, published by the Public Health on January 21st, is similar to that of the MRC, using data from a government briefing on January 17th and taking into account the transport of aircraft, trains and roads, it is estimated that the most likely number of people infected in Wuhan on that day was 1,343, while the most likely number of cases in provinces and cities other than Wuhan was 300.

Gabriel Leung, chair professor of Public Health Medicine at the University of Hong Kong, said on January 21 that the model took into account recent epidemic prevention measures in Wuhan and cities around the world, and based optimistic estimates on a 75 percent reduction in virus transmission from the initial stage, by the seventh day of the Lunar New Year, there will be an increase of 1-2 cases in foreign countries, with the highest possible increase of 70 cases in other provinces and cities except Wuhan.

But for now, the University of Hong Kong's public health website has added a note to the study: "since the number of reported cases has doubled in 24 hours, the reported study is no longer valid and the model is being re-adjusted. " (the public health report is detailed in HKUMED.)

10
In the process of treating patients, how can medical staff protect themselves?

Depending on the exposure, health care workers may take different precautions:

Such as contact with the patient's blood, body fluids, secretions, excreta, vomit and contaminated materials, must wear clean gloves, gloves after washing hands.

May Be affected by the patient's blood, body fluids, secretions, such as spatter, to wear medical protective masks, goggles, wear long-sleeved anti-infiltration of body fluids isolation clothing, wear gloves.

For suspected patients or confirmed patients to do such as tracheal intubation, non-invasive ventilation, tracheotomy, cardiopulmonary resuscitation, bronchoscopy and other check-up action, we should adopt air isolation measures as if wearing a medical protective mask, the eyes should wear goggles or face mask, wear long-sleeve isolation clothing to prevent body fluid infiltration, wear gloves, in addition, the operation should be in a well-ventilated room; The number of people in the room is limited to the minimum amount of care and support needed by the patient.

All of the above protective supplies once the patient's blood, body fluids, secretions and other pollution, it is necessary to replace. Stethoscopes, thermometers, sphygmomanometers and other medical instruments and care items for patients suspected or confirmed should also be used by special personnel, or should be cleaned and disinfected after each use.

Finally, medical institutions should also rationally allocate human resources and shift arrangements to avoid overwork of medical staff. Provide a nutritious diet to strengthen the immune system. Active Health Monitoring, including temperature and respiratory system symptoms, is carried out based on job characteristics and risk assessment results.

The epidemic spread of infectious diseases is a model full of variables. The nature of the disease itself, the density of people in the area, the flow of people, the timing of preventive measures, and the weather all have an impact. So there's no exact analogy, but there are several points in time.

The prevention and treatment of all infectious diseases can be solved by "three measures" : 1) controlling the source of infection, 2) cutting off the route of transmission, and 3) protecting the susceptible population.

On the first thing, we're moving faster this time than we did when we had SARS.

On December 30, the medical administration and Medical Administration Department of Wuhan Health Commission issued an emergency notice on the treatment of pneumonia of unknown cause, saying that since December, pneumonia of unknown cause has started to appear in Wuhan.

On January 7, CDC experts isolated the COVID-19; on January 10, professor Zhang Yongzhen of the Fudan University and his team published the full genome sequence of the virus on the academic website of global viral research.

In other words, it took less than a month from the onset of the disease to the identification of the pathogen.

SARS, on the other hand, took five months for the coronavirus to be detected by foreign scientists and confirmed by WHO as the pathogen.

Next, it is directed at the characteristics of pathogens and diseases, rapid prevention and control. This is not just a matter of the health care system, because information disclosure, disease control, mobilization and other work, need to be completed by the government.

But since January 11, the number of confirmed cases announced by the Wuhan Municipal Health and Health Commission has risen from 41 to 45 until January 16. On January 20th the Official infectious included the disease in its list of diseases.

"Wuhan Pneumonia" before spreading to the whole country, why did not break out first in Hubei Province?

05

"Wuhan Pneumonia" before spreading to the whole country, why did not break out first in Hubei Province?

On the subject, cEO  , founder of urban quadrant and Secretary General of Cloud Platform Innovation Center of Beijing Urban Planning & Design Institute, and his team conducted a comprehensive study of tencent migration data and other data from 2018 to 2019, some interesting perspectives are given as to why

1) cities in Hubei Province, as well as cities in and around Hubei Province such as Yueyang, Xinyang and Jiujiang, should strengthen the screening of long-distance bus passengers from the "Wuhan Metropolitan Area" (Note: With Wuhan as the center, covering the urban cluster of eight large and medium-sized cities around Huangshi, Ezhou, Huanggang, Xiaogan, Xianning, Xiantao, Xianning and Tianmen) .

This is because the inner cities of the metropolitan area have daily high frequency contact with the inner cities, even commuting. However, only Huanggang has been reported in the figures so far, so there is a possibility that the situation in Hubei Province is underestimated or not properly accounted for.

2) cities such as Beijing, Shanghai, Chengdu, Guangzhou, Changsha, Xiangyang, Jingzhou and Yichang should strengthen the screening of railway passengers from Wuhan; cities such as Beijing, Kunming, Shenyang and Chengdu should also strengthen the screening of flights from Wuhan.

Among these cities, Changsha and Kunming are the new first-tier cities with high degree of contact with Wuhan, but the number of epidemic people is still relatively small. These two cities are the central cities of their respective metropolitan areas, but also an important node of the urban agglomerations, so the two cities if the outbreak of disease, there is a certain ability to spread.

3) the spread of "Wuhan Pneumonia" to Beijing, Shanghai, Guangzhou, Shenzhen, several first-tier cities, medical conditions, information transparency, as well as anti-sars experience, the people's awareness of self-protection is high, so the situation is relatively optimistic.

In addition to presenting the results of the current analysis, Mao Mingrui also stressed that the current epidemic areas must disclose detailed public data, so as to effectively increase the awareness of self-protection of residents in the epidemic areas. The current practice of opening up data according to the province is not conducive to civil protection, not conducive to appropriate responses from all sectors, and not conducive to scholars carrying out valuable research.

There is no vaccine or specific drug for COVID-19, so how long will it take for the vaccine to be developed, marketed, and then marketed to consumers?

06

There is no vaccine or specific drug for COVID-19, so how long will it take for the vaccine to be developed, marketed, and then marketed to consumers?

During the SARS outbreak, academician Zhong Nanshan proposed the treatment of "hormone shock therapy" , because large doses of glucocorticoid shock can effectively control this immune pathological response, glucocorticoid was then heavily used in the emergency treatment of SARS. But it has also led to osteonecrosis of the femoral head in many patients, as well as pulmonary dysfunction and other drug side effects.

After sequencing the genome of the COVID-19, the U.S. now includes teams at the NIH and the Baylor College of Medicine, as well as in Texas and New York, and at the University of Saskatchewan in Canada, and a team of Chinese scientists are already working on a vaccine.

"coronaviruses are a relatively simple vaccine target, " says Peter Hotz, a vaccine scientist at the Baylor College of Medicine, so they are less difficult to develop than vaccines against other viruses, such as HIV or influenza.

After the vaccine is developed, it is expected to take several months to complete the first phase of clinical trials and wait more than a year for its official launch.

07
Where is the "new" COVID-19 of 2020 compared with the SARS virus?

There are six previously known human coronaviruses: Four of them are more common in humans and less pathogenic; the other two, SARS coronavirus and Mers coronavirus, cause severe respiratory disease.

This COVID-19 is different from all known human coronaviruses.

On January 10,2020, Professor Zhang Yongzhen's team at Fudan University published the genome sequence of Covid-19 for the first time on the virological.org  . Based on the genome sequence, hao Pei, a researcher at the Shanghai Pasteur Institute of the Chinese Academy of Sciences, and his team published their findings on Jan. 21 in the Journal COVID-19. In the paper, Hao and his team reveal the origin of the COVID-19 virus and its genetic relationship to SARS coronavirus and MERS coronavirus.

The COVID-19 virus is similar to the SARS virus in that it acts as an immunopathologic response -- as if when the virus enters the body, it invades living cells, inducing them to attack their own cells, this leads to a severe inflammatory reaction.

08
Where does COVID-19 come from, and what is its infectiousness and variability?

After the SARS outbreak in 2003, researchers discovered that the SARS coronavirus was transmitted by "bat-civet-man" , and the international community later discovered that bats were the coronavirus's stronghold. Hao's team compared the entire genome of COVID-19, SARS coronavirus and Mers coronavirus to find that the viruses share a common ancestor. Therefore, the natural host of Wuhan Coronavirus may also be bats.

A paper published Jan. 22 in the Journal of Medicalvirology by Peking University, the Guangxi University of Chinese Medicine, the Ningbo University and others suggests, snakes are the most likely wildlife reservoir to cause the current Covid-192019-ncov outbreak. In other words, the COVID-19 may have traveled the same route as the bat-snake-man.

According to Hao's team, COVID-19 shares the same pathogenesis as the SARS virus, which infects humans through the interaction of the S-protein with human ACE2 in COVID-19 Pseudostratified columnar epithelium, this means that the virus provides a basis for human-to-human transmission.

In an interview with the CCTV-13 News 1 + 1, Academician Zhong Nanshan confirmed to the public that the COVID-19 will "pass from one person to another. " .

In an interview with the Beijing News on Jan. 21, WHO officials said that the latest reported infection "has no clear evidence of sustained human-to-human COVID-19. ". According to Zhu Huachen, an associate professor at the public health of the University of Hong Kong who has long studied viral emerging infectious diseases, "the transmission of the virus is cut off after one or two generations" , making it difficult to achieve efficient transmission or even super-transmission.

When the latest case data were released on Jan. 22, Li Bin, deputy director of the COVID-19, said there was still a possibility of mutation.

On the morning of January 22 local time, the World Health Organization convened an emergency committee meeting in Geneva. After two days of discussion, the World Health Organization Organization announced at a press conference held in the evening of January 23 local time and in the early hours of January 24 China Standard Time, the COVID-19 outbreak will not be defined as "a public health emergency of international concern" for the time being.

According to the definition of the IHR, an "international public health emergency" means "a public health risk to other countries through the international spread of a disease" , and may require a coordinated "international response" to "extraordinary" events. Since the rules were introduced in the Mid-2000s, only five announcements have been made about H1N1, poliomyelitis, Ebola and Zika.

09
Is it credible to predict that the number of people infected with COVID-19 pneumonia in Wuhan would be in the thousands?

At present, non-traditional public health data such as traffic data, mobile communication data and social media data can be used to help estimate and even predict epidemic risk. Both the Imperial College London's MRC Global Infectious Disease Analysis Centre and the public health used Wuhan traffic data as a key basis for modelling the COVID-19 outbreak.

In the MRC's research methods, it is mainly to use the confirmed cases reported from abroad to push back the situation in Wuhan, there are four key parameters in the model: The number of confirmed cases abroad, the number of passengers departing from Wuhan Airport every day, the number of passengers per day at Wuhan Airport, and the average incubation period of the virus. The data for these four parameters is inherently elastic (for example, the Virus latency is usually estimated at 10 days, but it could also be 8 days) , so the estimated number of infected people is a large range.

Using the data reported by the government on January 18, the MRC has given the upper and lower limits of the maximum number of people infected in Wuhan on January 18, ranging from 1,000 to 9,700 respectively, and the maximum possible value of 4,000 under standard parameters. (see MRC report in News / Wuhan Coronavirus)

At a press conference of the State Council Office on January 22, responding to the findings, Takatomi, an academician at the Chinese Academy of Sciences and Director of the Chinese Center for Disease Control and Prevention, said: "everyone knows that to recognize any new thing, especially a virus like this, must be 'fact is fact, knowledge theory is theory' . And I think that as you know more about this virus, you will be able to test this model. "What we know now is not the model that the scientist has calculated. "

The mathematical model, published by the Public Health on January 21st, is similar to that of the MRC, using data from a government briefing on January 17th and taking into account the transport of aircraft, trains and roads, it is estimated that the most likely number of people infected in Wuhan on that day was 1,343, while the most likely number of cases in provinces and cities other than Wuhan was 300.

Gabriel Leung, chair professor of Public Health Medicine at the University of Hong Kong, said on January 21 that the model took into account recent epidemic prevention measures in Wuhan and cities around the world, and based optimistic estimates on a 75 percent reduction in virus transmission from the initial stage, by the seventh day of the Lunar New Year, there will be an increase of 1-2 cases in foreign countries, with the highest possible increase of 70 cases in other provinces and cities except Wuhan.

But for now, the University of Hong Kong's public health website has added a note to the study: "since the number of reported cases has doubled in 24 hours, the reported study is no longer valid and the model is being re-adjusted. " (the public health report is detailed in HKUMED.)

In the process of treating patients, how can medical staff protect themselves?

Depending on the exposure, health care workers may take different precautions:

Such as contact with the patient's blood, body fluids, secretions, excreta, vomit and contaminated materials, must wear clean gloves, gloves after washing hands.

May Be affected by the patient's blood, body fluids, secretions, such as spatter, to wear medical protective masks, goggles, wear long-sleeved anti-infiltration of body fluids isolation clothing, wear gloves.

For suspected patients or confirmed patients to do such as tracheal intubation, non-invasive ventilation, tracheotomy, cardiopulmonary resuscitation, bronchoscopy and other check-up action, we should adopt air isolation measures as if wearing a medical protective mask, the eyes should wear goggles or face mask, wear long-sleeve isolation clothing to prevent body fluid infiltration, wear gloves, in addition, the operation should be in a well-ventilated room; The number of people in the room is limited to the minimum amount of care and support needed by the patient.

All of the above protective supplies once the patient's blood, body fluids, secretions and other pollution, it is necessary to replace. Stethoscopes, thermometers, sphygmomanometers and other medical instruments and care items for patients suspected or confirmed should also be used by special personnel, or should be cleaned and disinfected after each use.

Finally, medical institutions should also rationally allocate human resources and shift arrangements to avoid overwork of medical staff. Provide a nutritious diet to strengthen the immune system. Active Health Monitoring, including temperature and respiratory system symptoms, is carried out based on job characteristics and risk assessment results.

All of the above protective supplies once the patient's blood, body fluids, secretions and other pollution, it is necessary to replace. Stethoscopes, thermometers, sphygmomanometers and other medical instruments and care items for patients suspected or confirmed should also be used by special personnel, or should be cleaned and disinfected after each use.

Finally, medical institutions should also rationally allocate human resources and shift arrangements to avoid overwork of medical staff. Provide a nutritious diet to strengthen the immune system. Active Health Monitoring, including temperature and respiratory system symptoms, is carried out based on job characteristics and risk assessment results.
